phenomenological parameters, such as lag times and maximal growth rates that are
already obtainable from standard fitting procedures. We describe here an
analytical approach based on fixed-point analysis, which provides
self-consistent solutions for the growth of filamentous structures that can, in
addition to elongation, undergo internal fracturing and monomer-dependent
nucleation as mechanisms for generating new free ends acting as growth sites.
Our results generalise the analytical expression for sigmoidal growth kinetics
from the Oosawa theory for nucleated polymerisation to the case of fragmenting
filaments. We determine the corresponding growth laws in closed form and derive
from first principles a number of relationships which have been empirically
established for the kinetics of the self-assembly of amyloid fibrils.},
